Control file for Drift self-improvement loop.
Check this file before every cycle.

Current status: RUNNING
Direction:

NEVER STOP. Keep improving until human changes status to STOP.
Commit frequently. Don't publish TestFlight unless asked.
Check this file before every improvement cycle.

=== PRIORITY 1: AI CHAT QUALITY ===

The AI chat must be world-class at three things:

1) FOOD LOGGING VIA CHAT
   - Multi-turn conversation: "I had rice" → "how much?" → "1 cup" → logged
   - Handle ambiguity: "I had coffee" → "black or with milk?" → smart follow-up
   - Show what the agent is doing: "Searching for rice..." → "Found: Rice (206cal). Opening log..."
   - When food is found in DB, open the food log sheet pre-filled (never log silently)
   - Test with synthetic queries: "log dal and roti", "I just had 2 samosas for lunch", "add a protein shake"
   - Handle corrections: "actually it was 3 not 2"

2) NATURAL CONVERSATION FLOW
   - Study how Claude Code CLI handles multi-turn — the leaked repo shows great patterns
   - Context should flow naturally between turns
   - AI should remember what was discussed in the session
   - When AI doesn't know, it should ask clarifying questions instead of guessing
   - Responses should feel human — no "Based on your data," preambles
   - Keep responses under 3 sentences unless user asks for detail

3) WORKOUT TEMPLATE CREATION VIA CHAT
   - "I want to do a push day" → show available templates or help create one
   - "Add bench press 3x10" → build a workout step by step
   - Show the user what's being built: display the workout as it forms
   - Let them start the workout from chat

=== PRIORITY 2: MODEL EVALUATION HARNESS ===

Build a gold-standard test harness for evaluating LLM quality:

- Create a test suite of 50+ synthetic queries with expected responses
- Categories: food logging, health questions, workout advice, biomarker interpretation, general
- Measure precision (correct actions triggered) and recall (queries handled vs. falling to fallback)
- Score response quality: references real data? appropriate length? no hallucination?
- Make it easy to swap models and compare: Qwen2.5-1.5B vs SmolLM2-360M vs future models
- Store results in a JSON/markdown report so humans can review
- Run as part of test suite: `xcodebuild test`
- This harness lets us confidently upgrade models without regression

=== PRIORITY 3: INFERENCE OPTIMIZATION ===

Speed without quality loss:

- Research building llama.cpp from source as SPM package for Metal GPU support
  (prebuilt xcframework has A19 Pro shader incompatibility — building from source fixes this)
  GPU inference would be 10-20x faster than current CPU-only
- Explore prompt caching: system prompt tokens could be pre-computed and reused
- Profile where time is spent: tokenization vs prompt eval vs generation
- Try different quantizations: Q4_K_M vs Q5_K_M vs Q8_0 — benchmark quality vs speed
- Consider smaller context window for simple queries (512 vs 2048)
- Research: can we use Apple's Neural Engine via CoreML for even faster inference?

=== PRIORITY 4: MEDICAL REPORT EXTRACTION ===

When AI model is loaded, use it to improve:

- Lab report OCR: LLM fallback already exists — test it with real reports, improve accuracy
- Nutrition label parsing: use LLM to extract from photos when regex fails
- Food name normalization: "PBJ" → "peanut butter and jelly sandwich"
- Create test cases with sample lab report text to validate extraction quality

=== PRIORITY 5: BUG HUNTING ===

Before adding features, ensure stability:

- Look at recent commits (last 150+) — that's where bugs hide
- Write tests for every new feature added in this session
- Check edge cases: empty DB, no HealthKit, no internet, model not downloaded
- Test the full flow: download model → load → chat → log food → verify in Food tab

=== RESEARCH IDEAS (curate, don't implement) ===

Save findings to Docs/ai-improvement-ideas.md:

1) Exercise demonstration: how to show users form videos/images for exercises
2) Image-based food logging: photo → describe → log (needs vision model or classifier)
3) Voice input: iOS speech-to-text → AI chat → hands-free food logging
4) Weekly AI summary: background task generates weekly health insight notification
5) Fine-tuning: create health Q&A dataset, fine-tune Qwen2.5-1.5B for better domain answers
6) Model distillation: train SmolLM2-360M to match Qwen quality for faster inference
7) On-device embeddings: MiniLM for semantic food search instead of keyword matching
8) Apple Neural Engine: CoreML conversion of the model for ANE acceleration

=== HOW TO WORK ===

- Check .claude-stop status before every cycle
- Commit after each meaningful improvement
- Run tests after every change: `xcodebuild test`
- Build after every change: `xcodebuild build`
- Push to git frequently
- Log what you did in commit messages
- When stuck, research on the web
- When something isn't clear, err on the side of not breaking existing functionality

Status options:
- RUNNING: continue the loop
- STOP: finish current work, commit, halt
- PAUSE: commit and wait for instructions
- REDIRECT: read Direction field, apply changes, set back to RUNNING

To give feedback during a session, change status to REDIRECT and write in Direction.
Examples:
- "Focus only on bug fixes for the next hour"
- "Skip workout template work, focus on food logging"
- "The model quality got worse, revert last change"
- "Publish TestFlight now"
